Can the Euro be fixed?
Recently, French-German Finance Minister Olaf Scholz brought up the option of Greece leaving the Euro, hoping to send a signal that no member state is exempt from the strict discipline of the currency union.
Actually, his proposal triggered a big discussion about the principles of the Euro, the governance model of the Euro, and the reasons for the existence of the Euro.
Before Scholz's proposal, European leaders had already noticed the report on the future of the Euro written by European Commission President von der Leyen and her colleagues from other EU institutions, but the new dispute over Greece has led many decision-makers to return to the original starting point.
At the same time, citizens are questioning why they have to share the same currency?
Is it meaningful? Can there be a consensus on Greece's future?
Currency is like a nation, its establishment requires myths.
Traditional wisdom believes that the Euro was Germany's political price to pay to France in exchange for reunification.
In fact, German reunification was only the last step in a project that was formed in the 1980s to solve a long-standing problem.
European governments strongly opposed floating exchange rates, believing they were incompatible with the single market; at the same time, they did not want to maintain a long-term currency mechanism dominated by the German central bank.
A truly European currency founded on German principles seems to be the best solution.
Looking back, German reunification was more of a curse than a blessing.
At the time when exchange rates were locked in 1999, Germany was overvalued, facing significant economic difficulties; France was undervalued, experiencing prosperity.
Over the next decade, the imbalance gradually emerged between a resurgent Germany and countries that experienced a credit boom due to low interest rates.
And with the outbreak of the 2008 global financial crisis, these conditions became the perfect storm.
No one knows what Europe will become without the euro.
Will the fixed exchange rate system be maintained or collapse?
Will the German mark be overvalued again?
Will countries reintroduce trade barriers and end the single market?
Will a housing bubble emerge in Spain?
Will there be more or less government reform?
It is impossible to establish a baseline evaluation of the impact of the euro through reverse analysis.
This is not a reason for self-satisfaction.
In the past 15 years, the economic performance of the eurozone has been disappointing, and its political system must be held accountable for it.
The true importance is whether the common European currency is still important for the future.
This issue is often avoided, because the cost of exiting the Euro is unbearable to imagine (and if the Eurozone were to collapse during the crisis, and exacerbating tensions between participating countries, the cost would further increase)
Furthermore, abolishing the Euro may unleash the dark forces of nationalism and protectionism.
However, Kevin O'Rourke of Oxford University recently pointed out that this view is not sufficient.
Logically, it is equivalent to suggesting that a couple should maintain their marriage because the cost of divorce is too high.
So, is the Euro still meaningful?
Originally, people expected the euro to bring three major economic benefits.
People assumed that a single currency would promote economic integration and consolidate long-term growth in Europe.
On the contrary, intra-regional trade and investment in the euro zone have grown poorly, and the growth potential has actually been weakened.
This is partly because national governments have not further integrated on the basis of currency unification to build the euro zone into a super economic power, but rather tried to preserve their remaining power.
This may be in accordance with the logic of governance, but it is of no use in economics: the European giant internal market is one of its major assets, and it cannot be wasted to strengthen the internal market.
Secondly, people hoped that the euro would become a major international currency (especially considering that few countries can meet the necessary legal, market, and policy system requirements).
According to the latest data from the European Central Bank, this hope has been basically realized.
The international use of the euro ranks second to the US dollar, which has helped Europe continue to influence the global economic order rather than becoming an insignificant entity.
Thirdly, people (naively) believed that the institutions based on the euro could improve the overall quality of economic policy, as if the European overall policy level was naturally higher than the national policy level.
After the 2008 global financial crisis, a severe test arrived: the euro zone overestimated the fiscal dimension of the crisis and underestimated its financial dimension, and therefore performed worse than the United States and the United Kingdom.
If the euro is to bring prosperity, further policy and institutional reforms are necessary.
However, formulating and implementing a schedule requires a broad and consistent understanding of the nature of the problem.
The continued debate over the Greek issue shows that Europe is still far from reaching a consensus: participating countries have conflicting analyses of the root causes of the debt crisis, and therefore their prescriptions are also conflicting.
Richard Cooper of Harvard University once observed that in the early stage of international cooperation in public health, the governance of global diseases was greatly limited by the different transmission patterns of diseases among countries.
Each country prefers joint action, but cannot form a consistent plan, as they have different opinions on how infectious diseases are transmitted from one country to another.
This is the problem that the euro zone is facing today.
Luckily, it is not an unsolvable problem, as the establishment of the European Stability Mechanism, the launch of the banking union, etc. have proven that it is not.
The inconsistency did not stop the European Central Bank from taking decisive actions, which shows that institutions do matter.
However, reform and action started to be implemented only recently, and it was under the pressure of a severe crisis, which makes us clearly aware of the difficulty of reaching a consensus.
Europe cannot afford to delay and pretend anymore.
Member states of the euro zone must form a consistent schedule for governance and political reform, turning the currency union into a prosperity engine, or else they will sink into repeated disputes and crises, until citizens lose patience or the market loses trust.
Clarity is the prerequisite for serious discussion and grand reform.
Today, all major parties have a duty to clarify what they consider indispensable, what they cannot accept, and what they will use as bargaining chips to get what they want.
